Decentralized Inference and Apple's Private AI Cloud Compute
Seth Bloomberg

Jun 13, 2024 ⋅  8 min read

Earlier this week, Apple showcased a slew of new AI features and services for its hardware product line. The announcement also included broad-stroke details around Apple’s Private Cloud Compute (PCC), which highlights an ever-growing sector of importance within the AI x Crypto stack — decentralized inference.

Within the AI x Crypto context, decentralized inference refers to the ability to add a layer of accountability to an AI model. Users need some assurance that, for some given AI model and input data, the output truly is what is returned to the user. These assurances are difficult to grant when the models are owned and operated by centralized entities. Generally, the “assurances” boil down to simply trusting the model operators.

The above-described trust model is the standard for the Web2 setting. However, as onchain applications begin to leverage AI systems, trust must be replaced by some form of accountability and verifiability. Numerous teams are now working within the AI x Crypto vertical to achieve these ends, and they are leveraging familiar tools — ZK proofs and cryptoeconomics.

Decentralized and Verifiable Inference

To use an AI-powered product, the underlying model is inferenced. When you ask ChatGPT to summarize an article, you are inferencing OpenAI’s model (e.g., GPT-4o, GPT-3.5, etc). That model is hosted on some server at a large data center, which enables it to scale up and down to meet the current levels of demand. Once the summarized article is returned, that completes the cycle of a centralized inference workflow.

In the above workflow, OpenAI represents the centralized point of trust. Users must trust that the model they are paying for is actually processing the inference. Additionally, there is trust that OpenAI will not tamper with the output. Currently, most users accept the premise that OpenAI is acting honestly. However, as AI becomes less of a toy or fun product and more akin to mission-critical infrastructure for individuals, institutions, and governments, removing points of centralized trust will be of paramount importance.

Decentralized Inference Methodologies – ZK, Cryptoeconomic, and TEEs

Onchain environments seek to replace these points of centralization with verification mechanisms. The current set of tools that decentralized inference builders are using maps well to how rollups are secured (i.e., ZK proofs and fraud proofs). Similar to the rollup environment, each approach has associated tradeoffs around economics, security guarantees, and speed to market.

Zero Knowledge Machine Learning – zkML

The goal of zkML is to produce cryptographic proof that a certain output was produced from a specific set of data processed by an AI model. Just as is the case with ZK rollups, users of zkML systems do not need to trust the entity running the infrastructure that generates the proof. A proof verifier, typically encoded into an onchain smart contract, ensures the correctness of the proof. In practice, this approach has technical and economic hurdles.

Both challenges become evident when considering the work of Modulus, one of the leading teams building in this category. Compiling an AI model into something that can generate a ZK proof (i.e., a circuit) is a non-trivial, technical challenge. In Modulus’ most recent paper, they describe the technical architecture they arrived at for creating a ZK circuit for a specific type of AI model. While it’s difficult to calculate the “cost” of arriving at this technical approach, their work undoubtedly took many months of specific R&D and also relies on tangential ZK advancements from other ZK research teams.

The economics of creating ZK proofs are twofold — proof generation costs and proof verification costs. Per Modulus’ paper, they achieve an impressive ~180x compute overhead compared to the “non-ZK” approach. In somewhat oversimplified terms, this implies that for every $1 of normal compute costs (i.e., the compute cost of a single AI model inference), the ZK proof generation of this AI model adds an additional overhead cost of $180. In just January 2023, the Modulus team cited this overhead cost as being ~1,000x, implying rapid progress is occurring on the proof generation cost front.

Proof verification costs have more flexibility than proof generation costs. Ethereum mainnet has been the favored chain for verifying proofs. Generally, the lower bound on proof verification is ~250,000 gas (i.e., $25, assuming an ETH price of $3,200 and a gas price of 30 gwei). Using Ethereum is not a necessity, though; multiple teams, such as Hyle and Aligned Layer, are developing optimized and purpose-built chains to lower the costs of proof verification.

The bottom line for zkML is that the high-cost burdens are typically passed on to the user, representing significant barriers to adoption, but the cryptographic guarantees of ZK proofs provide the strongest form of inference verification.

Cryptoeconomic Machine Learning – Optimistic ML

One of the pioneers of optimistic ML (opML) is Ora protocol, along with Hyperspace. Functionally, opML systems somewhat mirror optimistic rollups. The opML approach does not require ZK proofs but rather relies on multiple parties redundantly computing the specified inference request. If these parties disagree on the outcome, they can begin a “verification game,” where the challenger tries to disprove the results by demonstrating the erroneous step. Theoretically, as long as there is a single honest verifier entity, then the opML system is secure.

On the surface, the costs of these opML systems are lower than zkML. As long as the cost of compensating the opML verifier entities is lower than the zkML proof costs (both proof generation and verification), then the opML approach makes economic sense. However, given the nascency of permissionless fraud proofs, it’s unclear how much of a markup a verifying party will require for its services. Additionally, similar to optimistic rollups, opML systems effectively have a challenge window in which the results of inference requests cannot be trusted and, therefore, are not usable within applications. For optimistic rollups, this challenge window is usually days, but opML systems may have shorter windows given the demand from potentially latency-sensitive applications.

A variation of the opML approach is a stake-and-slash model. This approach avoids both ZK and fraud proofs, purely relying on a certain set of compute providers to all process the same inference request (i.e., perform redundant computation) and come to a consensus on the correct output. If there is disagreement on the output, those in the minority would be slashed. The glaring issue here is the risk of collusion between those entities processing compute requests.

One underappreciated benefit of this approach is the ability to scale the security backing a specific application. We discussed this general approach in our recent Arweave and AO report. For example, a small AI consumer application may wish to pay only for a small number of nodes to redundantly compute the results of an inference request, which lowers the cost for users. On the other hand, a DeFi protocol with billions of dollars worth of economic activity will likely pay the higher cost of more nodes in return for greater security guarantees.

Trusted Execution Environment ML - teeML

While each approach to decentralized inference is in its early stages, teeML is perhaps the newest architecture. There’s much to be unpacked with Trusted Execution Environments (TEEs), but in a simplified and ideal case, a developer can deploy a program to a TEE, and the TEE can produce attestations that the program it’s running has not been tampered with in any way. TEEs are used widely in the computing space, with one of the most relevant examples being the secure enclave within every Apple iPhone. Numerous projects, including Phala, Marlin, and Aizel, are now developing decentralized inference protocols leveraging TEEs.

The teeML approach allows for inference compute providers to leverage a TEE, which provides attestations to its computations. Many newer, top-tier GPUs (e.g., NVIDIA’s H100) effectively have a TEE component. Although the attestations do give assurances that the inference process was handled correctly, there are still trust assumptions, such as trusting the program and TEE were properly configured.

The Marlin team claims the teeML approach only carries a 10-15% computation overhead, which is obviously orders of magnitude more performant than the zkML approach. The attestations provided by TEEs are fundamentally different and weaker than ZK proofs, but they do provide a some form of assurance and can be posted onchain.

Apple’s PCC and Verifiable Inference Convergence

So, how does Apple’s PCC connect back to the decentralized inference layer within the AI x Crypto vertical? Well, PCC effectively sounds a lot like a form of verifiable inference. For example, in Apple’s blog post, they have a specific section on “verifiable transparency,” where they discuss posting the code running on the PCC nodes to “an append-only and cryptographically tamper-proof transparency log.” Additionally, the architecture of PCC nodes is similar to that of TEEs.

However, Apple’s primary focus is to ensure the privacy of user data. This focus is at odds with the decentralized inference approaches noted above; this is particularly true for both the zkML and opML strategies. Both approaches rely on effectively having the input data in plaintext. In an onchain setting, though, data privacy is currently of lesser importance relative to verifiable inference.

In any case, this is obvious, positive validation for those teams building decentralized inference protocols. It points to the fact that even the Web2 giants, such as Apple, acknowledge the importance of removing trust assumptions from a technology that will eventually become a massively critical piece of infrastructure – generative AI models – for both onchain and offchain applications.
